{"id":"1108.0871","submitter":"Martin Z. Bazant","authors":"Ali Mani and Martin Z. Bazant (MIT)","title":"Desalination shocks in microstructures","comments":"14 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.84.061504","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn physics.chem-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Salt transport in bulk electrolytes is limited by diffusion and convection,\nbut in microstructures with charged surfaces (e.g. microfluidic devices, porous\nmedia, soils, or biological tissues) surface conduction and electro-osmotic\nflow also contribute to ionic fluxes. For small applied voltages, these effects\nlead to well known linear electrokinetic phenomena. In this paper, we predict\nsome surprising nonlinear dynamics that can result from the competition between\nbulk and interfacial transport at higher voltages. When counter-ions are\nselectively removed by a membrane or electrode, a \"desalination shock\" can\npropagate through the microstructure, leaving in its wake an ultrapure\nsolution, nearly devoid of co-ions and colloidal impurities. We elucidate the\nbasic physics of desalination shocks and develop a mathematical theory of their\nexistence, structure, and stability, allowing for slow variations in surface\ncharge or channel geometry. Via asymptotic approximations and similarity\nsolutions, we show that desalination shocks accelerate and sharpen in narrowing\nchannels, while they decelerate and weaken, and sometimes disappear, in\nwidening channels. These phenomena may find applications in separations\n(desalination, decontamination, biological assays) and energy storage\n(batteries, supercapacitors) involving electrolytes in microstructures.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Aug 2011 15:41:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-30"}
